wnt induced dephosphorylation of axin releases beta catenin from the axin complex the nusse lab stanford university skip to main content area login username password request new password home search this site main publications contact wnt homepage home publications wnt induced dephosphorylation of axin releases beta catenin from the axin complex submitted by admin on thu 10 14 2010 22 44 title wnt induced dephosphorylation of axin releases beta catenin from the axin complex publication type journal article year of publication 1999 authors willert k shibamoto s nusse r journal genes dev volume 13 pagination 1768 1773 date published jul issn 0890 9369 print 0890 9369 linking abstract the stabilization of beta catenin is a key regulatory step during cell fate changes and transformations to tumor cells several interacting proteins including axin apc and the protein kinase gsk 3beta are implicated in regulating beta catenin phosphorylation and its subsequent degradation wnt signaling stabilizes beta catenin but it was not clear whether and how wnt signaling regulates the beta catenin complex here we show that axin is dephosphorylated in response to wnt signaling the dephosphorylated axin binds beta catenin less efficiently than the phosphorylated form thus wnt signaling lowers axin's affinity for beta catenin thereby disengaging beta catenin from the degradation machinery tagged xml bibtex google scholar main publications contact all rights reserved site design by roel nusse and xinhong lim powered by drupal an open source content management system
